have no reason to trust.

18:12.091 --> 18:15.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL LEITER: There's no doubt
that some
cases like Syria make it more
difficult.

18:16.095 --> 18:20.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think the one you just
repeated was
really exaggerating how hard it
is.

18:20.933 --> 18:22.468 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We still have lots of databases.

18:22.568 --> 18:23.636 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We have lots of information.

18:23.736 --> 18:24.770 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We know e-mail addresses.

18:24.870 --> 18:26.639 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We know phone numbers.

18:26.739 --> 18:29.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And searching those against the
wealth of
collection that the U.S.
intelligence community

18:29.976 --> 18:32.945 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has can make connections that
are important.

18:33.045 --> 18:35.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Further steps that have been
improved over
the past several years involve
looking at

18:35.848 --> 18:37.583 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
people's social media profile.

18:37.683 --> 18:39.819 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's really important to
understand.

18:39.919 --> 18:43.356 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We do have to demand that
countries from which
these people are coming are
cooperating with

18:43.456 --> 18:44.357 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the United States.

18:44.457 --> 18:46.425 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That should be part of the visa
process.

18:46.525 --> 18:49.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I think that's an important
step, that
we demand from these countries
that they provide

18:50.062 --> 18:51.831 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with us information.

18:51.931 --> 18:56.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the idea that we simply
can't get data
about these people, I think,
misunderstands

18:56.435 --> 19:00.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how the intelligence community
and the vetting
system has worked since 9/11.

19:00.473 --> 19:03.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Michael Leiter,
thank you very
much.

19:03.943 --> 19:12.184 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL LEITER: Great to be
here, Judy.

19:12.284 --> 19:14.086 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Thanks.

19:14.186 --> 19:19.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Aside from the
national security
concerns, the president's
executive order

19:19.258 --> 19:23.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has ignited a fierce debate on
its legality
and constitutionality.

19:23.863 --> 19:29.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We get two views, from Neal
Katyal, a former
acting solicitor general under
President Obama,

19:29.235 --> 19:33.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Jonathan Turley, a law
professor at George
Washington University.

19:33.439 --> 19:34.807 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jonathan, let's begin with you.

19:34.907 --> 19:40.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's talk about the law, 1965
Immigration
and Nationality Act.

19:40.379 --> 19:43.516 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What does it say, and how might
it impact
this executive order?

19:43.616 --> 19:45.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN TURLEY, Constitutional
Attorney,
George Washington University:
Well, I think

19:46.018 --> 19:47.853 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it can have an impact.

19:47.953 --> 19:53.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's no question that the law
says that
you cannot discriminate on the
basis of nationality

19:53.125 --> 19:54.894 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or place of origin.

19:54.994 --> 19:57.196 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that certainly helps the
challengers.

19:57.296 --> 20:02.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But like much else in this
debate, much of
that law has been distorted.

20:02.401 --> 20:03.869 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It only takes you so far.

20:03.969 --> 20:05.905 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
First of all, the law doesn't
apply to refugees.

20:06.005 --> 20:07.206 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It applies to immigrants.

20:07.306 --> 20:09.575 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's used when you have visa
issues.

20:09.675 --> 20:13.179 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Also, it doesn't cover religious
discrimination.

20:13.279 --> 20:22.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Also, in 1990, the act was
amended to exclude
procedural changes as a form of
discrimination.

20:22.221 --> 20:29.228 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that reduces the use of the
1965 law,
I think, as a serious challenge.

20:29.328 --> 20:34.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And also it means that much of
that order,
as they challenge, doesn't fall
under the

20:34.400 --> 20:36.168 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
law.

20:36.268 --> 20:39.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So even if one aspect might be
challenged
successfully, the other aspects
of the order

20:39.638 --> 20:41.440 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
would remain.

20:41.540 --> 20:45.511 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Federal courts have a
longstanding policy
to minimize the degree to which
they strike

20:45.611 --> 20:48.581 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
down a piece of legislation or
executive authority.

20:48.681 --> 20:53.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Neal, the way the
Immigration
and Nationality Act is written,
it mentioned

20:53.853 --> 20:56.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an individual's place of birth
or place of
residence.

20:56.789 --> 20:59.692 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It doesn't mention religion
specifically.

20:59.792 --> 21:04.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The executive order seemed to be
narrowly
tailored, trying to avoid the
use of the word

21:05.030 --> 21:06.665 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
religion.

21:06.765 --> 21:10.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in effect, did they write an
executive
order which would run afoul of
this law?

21:10.603 --> 21:12.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NEAL KATYAL, Former Acting U.S.
Solicitor
General: Oh, they did.

21:12.138 --> 21:14.907 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And don't be distracted by what
you just heard
from my friend Jonathan.

21:15.007 --> 21:19.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So -- but let me read the law,
first of all
-- quote -- "No person shall
receive any preference

21:19.912 --> 21:24.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or priority or be discriminated
against in
the issuance of an immigrant
visa because

21:24.884 --> 21:26.785 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of nationality."

21:26.886 --> 21:32.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, this is most of what the
executive order
does, discriminates on the basis
of nationality.

21:32.324 --> 21:34.260 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Forget about the refugee
provision.

21:34.360 --> 21:35.995 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's about green card holders.

21:36.095 --> 21:41.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's about anyone who is
applying for a visa,
a student, an employee of a
company.

21:41.300 --> 21:42.935 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You know, it applies broadly.

21:43.035 --> 21:45.671 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, of course, it doesn't reach
religious
discrimination.

21:45.771 --> 21:48.908 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
That's reached by the
Constitution, a separate
problem with the act.

21:49.008 --> 21:50.476 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So you have got two different
things.

21:50.576 --> 21:54.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have got, it violates the
statute and it
violates the Constitution.

21:54.813 --> 21:59.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And President Trump's advisers
are pretending
that this is 1952, in which this
1965 law

21:59.885 --> 22:00.786 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
didn't exist.

22:00.886 --> 22:02.488 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But, unfortunately, it does.

22:02.588 --> 22:06.926 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is landmark legislation
passed contemporaneously
with the Voting Rights Act.

22:07.026 --> 22:10.196 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it is just blatantly illegal
under that
law.

22:10.296 --> 22:13.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: All right, I feel
like I need
a gavel and a black robe here,
gentlemen.

22:13.532 --> 22:16.735 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Let's talk about the
Constitution for just
a moment, if we could.

22:16.835 --> 22:22.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First Amendment, very important
amendment,
as we all know, the
Establishment Clause.

22:22.408 --> 22:27.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jonathan, it seems on the face
of it that
you could make a pretty good
argument that

22:27.112 --> 22:32.918 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
this runs afoul of the
Establishment Clause,
which basically says the United
States doesn't

22:33.018 --> 22:34.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
get in the business of choosing
religions.

22:34.987 --> 22:39.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN TURLEY: Well, I think
the most vulnerable
aspect of the order is the one
that gives

22:39.825 --> 22:47.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
preference to minority
religions, and those
people that were persecuted
under them.

22:47.366 --> 22:49.868 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That certainly is the weakest
spot.

22:49.969 --> 22:55.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I'm still skeptical about
whether you
could make a successful
establishment claim.

22:55.140 --> 23:00.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a lot of cases that have
to be moved
aside to get from here to there
if you want

23:00.179 --> 23:02.014 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to strike down this law.

23:02.114 --> 23:06.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is true there's establishment
issues, but
there's also plenary power in
the hands of

23:06.485 --> 23:08.287 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a president.

23:08.387 --> 23:11.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: All right, so the
administration
is trying to be very clear about
saying this

23:11.557 --> 23:13.692 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is not a Muslim ban.

23:13.792 --> 23:18.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But let's listen to candidate
Trump December
a year ago, when he first rolled
out this

23:18.931 --> 23:20.733 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
idea.

23:20.833 --> 23:23.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP (R), President of
the United
States: Donald J. Trump is
calling for a total

23:23.302 --> 23:30.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and complete shutdown of Muslims
entering
the United States until our
country's representatives

23:30.709 --> 23:35.047 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can figure out what the hell is
going on.

23:35.147 --> 23:36.048 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

23:36.148 --> 23:37.950 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: OK.

23:38.050 --> 23:42.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, last Sunday, Rudy
Giuliani, close
adviser to President Trump in
the campaign

23:42.288 --> 23:44.023 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and through the transition, said
this:

23:44.123 --> 23:48.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RUDY GIULIANI (R), Former Mayor
of New York:
We focused on, instead religion,
danger.

23:48.394 --> 23:50.663 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's not based on religion.

23:50.763 --> 23:59.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's based on places where there
are substantial
evidence that people are sending
terrorists

23:59.938 --> 24:01.140 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
into our country.

24:01.240 --> 24:03.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: OK, counselor, so
you're arguing
this case.

24:03.742 --> 24:05.144 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Are those comments admissible?

24:05.244 --> 24:06.345 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NEAL KATYAL: Absolutely.

24:06.445 --> 24:08.247 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And here's the thing.

24:08.347 --> 24:12.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I was -- my last job was
the chief litigation
officer for the federal
government.

24:12.117 --> 24:16.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I made -- I made -- took use
of all the
precedents that Jonathan was
talking about

24:16.922 --> 24:18.557 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
broad power in immigration.

24:18.657 --> 24:22.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nothing extends as far as what
the president
has done.

24:22.161 --> 24:23.929 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
This is religious
discrimination.

24:24.029 --> 24:26.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And here's what the Supreme
Court has said
about that -- quote -- "The
clearest command

24:27.099 --> 24:31.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the First Amendment is that
one religious
denomination can't be officially
preferred

24:31.904 --> 24:33.005 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to another."

24:33.105 --> 24:36.608 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This executive order prefers
Christians to
Muslims.

24:36.709 --> 24:38.510 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
You have got it.

24:38.610 --> 24:42.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The president himself said so
contemporaneously
when he issued the executive
order to the

24:42.247 --> 24:43.716 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Christian Broadcast Network.

24:43.816 --> 24:45.851 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is just un-American and
unconstitutional.

24:45.951 --> 24:54.226 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Jonathan,
then-candidate Trump
and his adviser, Rudy Giuliani,
more recently,

24:54.326 --> 24:55.894 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
did they undermine their own
case?

24:55.994 --> 24:59.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JONATHAN TURLEY: Well, they
certainly undermined
their case.

24:59.565 --> 25:05.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, the Justice Department
attorneys are
in fetal positions every time
someone like

25:05.571 --> 25:08.774 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this speaks about the purpose of
a law.

25:08.874 --> 25:15.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the longstanding view of the
Justice Department
has been what legislators say
about a law

25:15.514 --> 25:17.783 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as to the motivation of the law
is not controlling.

25:17.883 --> 25:22.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have been in cases where the
Justice Department
has maintained that position,
that you have

25:22.388 --> 25:26.458 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to look at the law as to whether
it's lawful
or constitutional.

25:26.558 --> 25:32.965 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The court doesn't make
assumptions about -- or
speculation about the
motivations behind the

25:33.065 --> 25:34.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
law.

25:34.700 --> 25:38.670 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If the law has an otherwise bona
fide purpose,
the courts tend to go with that.

25:38.771 --> 25:45.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't see a court, any court
saying that
what a candidate said on the
trail is going

25:46.044 --> 25:49.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be material in terms of
whether this law
is struck down.

25:49.581 --> 25:52.084 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I'm surprised that Neal even
suggests
that.

25:52.184 --> 25:55.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have been in cases where those
types of
arguments have been raised, and
courts have

25:55.621 --> 25:56.855 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
shot it down.

25:56.955 --> 26:00.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For example, what if -- I mean,
Trump clearly
said that.

26:00.392 --> 26:05.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he then gave this law to
someone to draft,
and they came back with a law
that is not

26:05.464 --> 26:07.232 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a Muslim ban.

26:07.332 --> 26:11.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, I don't like the law, but I
don't think
any court is going to look at
this law and

26:11.870 --> 26:14.173 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
say it's a Muslim ban, because
it's not.

26:14.273 --> 26:18.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's plenty to object about
this law without
making it something it's not.

26:18.444 --> 26:20.245 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It doesn't ban all Muslims.

26:20.345 --> 26:23.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, I know people don't like to
say that
because they -- sort of like
Richard III,

26:23.949 --> 26:26.718 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
you want to think of your
enemies as worse
than they are.

26:26.819 --> 26:29.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You don't have to think about
this law as
worse than it is.

26:29.521 --> 26:32.191 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is not a Muslim ban on a
legal basis.

26:32.291 --> 26:36.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But, if it walks
like a duck,
talks like a duck, et cetera,
isn't this legal

26:36.628 --> 26:39.231 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
parsing that they have come to
this executive
order?

26:39.331 --> 26:44.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when you look at the context
and the comments,
you have to come to the
conclusion that at

26:44.136 --> 26:46.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
least religion was on their
minds in some
fashion.

26:46.271 --> 26:48.173 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NEAL KATYAL: Oh, religion was
more than on
their minds.

26:48.273 --> 26:50.075 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I think Jonathan is just wrong.

26:50.175 --> 26:54.213 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
This is a First Amendment
religion challenge
in which the motivations of the
law will be

26:54.313 --> 26:56.048 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
looked to, and courts do so.

26:56.148 --> 27:00.085 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And that's particularly
underscored here,
because what has the new defense
of this law

27:00.185 --> 27:01.186 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
been by the White House?

27:01.286 --> 27:03.255 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's, oh, we're not focused on
religion.

27:03.355 --> 27:04.523 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're focused on security.

27:04.623 --> 27:05.724 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: All right, much
to discuss
here.

27:05.824 --> 27:08.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Just in a word, going to the
Supreme Court?

27:08.527 --> 27:10.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Will this end up at the Supreme
Court?

27:10.462 --> 27:13.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NEAL KATYAL: No, I think this is
indefensible,
and I think that the Justice
Department, after

27:13.432 --> 27:17.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they lose in district court
after district
court, won't bring this even to
the Court

